<DOC><DOCNO> AP881129-0215 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-29-88 0033EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   11-29 0513</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0538</SECOND><DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   OPEC oil ministers have ended nearly twoweeks of tense discussions with a formal agreement to limitproduction and pump prices back toward the cartel's benchmark of $18per barrel.   But before the day was out, one oil minister indicated Mondaythat his new quota was not official, causing futures prices to backoff after a sharp runup.   The accord, which ended the winter meeting of the Organization ofPetroleum Exporting Countries, set an output ceiling of 18.5 millionbarrels a day for the 13 OPEC members, well under the 22.5 millionthat analysts estimate the cartel currently is pumping.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Major U.S. banks have boosted their prime lendingrates a half percentage point to 10.5 percent, the highest levelsince mid-1985.   The increase announced Monday will mean a jump in rates on avariety of consumer loans pegged to the prime, including home-equityloans. It also will raise borrowing costs for many companies thatrely on banks for financing.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The imbalance between what America imports andsells abroad narrowed to $28.53 billion in the July-Septemberquarter, a 5.4 percent decline, the government reports. It was thethird straight quarterly drop.   Through the first nine months of the year, the deficit is runningat an annual rate of $125.2 billion, compared with last year'srecord $160.3 billion deficit, the Commerce Department said Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. farm export volume hit a 6-year peak of147.5 million metric tons in the year ended Sept. 30, with Japanagain the biggest customer, the Agriculture Department says.   U.S. agricultural exports climbed to $35.2 billion this pastyear, while imports of farm products rose to a record $21 billion,the USDA said Monday.   That left the United States with a net agricultural trade surplusof $14.2 billion for fiscal 1988, compared with $7.22 billion a yearearlier.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Soviet and U.S. trade negotiators have agreedto extend through 1990 an agreement calling for the Soviet Union tobuy at least 9 million metric tons of grain a year from the UnitedStates.   The 27-month extension signed Monday in Moscow revived afive-year pact that expired Sept. 30.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal savings and loan regulators haveproposed an ``early intervention'' plan allowing the government totake over a failing institution before it becomes insolvent.   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which oversees the nation's3,028 federally insured Sandamp;Ls, also proposed Monday regulationsrequiring institutions with riskier commercial and stock investmentsto hold more capital, or reserve funds, than institutions investingmostly in residential mortgages, the traditional mainstay of thethrift industry.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Speculators have bid RJR Nabisco Inc.'s stockhigher on the hunch that fattened offers would emerge in theunprecedented auction for the food-and-tobacco giant, which haslured price tags as high as $26.8 billion.   Monday's price rise came as a company-imposed deadline for asecond round of bids approached today for the biggest corporatetakeover ever.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>